adical social transformation. He blazes an original path through the history of ideas, including Averroes (Ibn Rushd), Spinoza, and Marx as well as lesser-known figures. Here translated into English for the first time, Avicenna and the Aristotelian Left is at once a succinct summation of Bloch’s own idiosyncratic materialism, a provocative reconstruction of the Western philosophical tradition in light of its exchanges with Islamic thought, and a vital resource for contemporary debates about materialism in critical theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMaterialism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh1 aGoldman, Loren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Loren.1 aThompson, Peter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2019z978311070836308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195940uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/bloc1753440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231548144/original  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-070836-3  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles